result.execSummary:
The defendant Jerome Allen Crawford was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Substantial Battery (Substantial Bodily Harm With Intent To Cause Bodily Harm) [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse - Infliction of Physical Pain or Injury], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(2).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Jerome Allen Crawford appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Theodore OReilly in court for Jerome Allen Crawford.  Prosecuting attorney Ryan Jay Michaels in court for the State of Wisconsin. 
Plea and sentencing hearing held. Court held colloquy with the defendant regarding his right to have an in-person hearing. Parties have reached an agreement. State places offer on the record. Defense and defendant are in agreement.

Pursuant to negotiations and on the Motion of the State, Court Ordered Counts 1 AND 3 DISMISSED BUT READ IN for the purpose of sentencing.

AS TO COUNTS 2 AND 4; Defendant changes plea(s) to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Defendant further advised that if not a US citizen, deportation is possible. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, Addendum, and Elements/Jury Instructions received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea(s).  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  

Sentencing proceeded. Statements by parties and defendant. Additional statements made by S.A.C. and S.E.

AS TO COUNT 2: The court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM term in the Wisconsin State Prison of 3 YEARS, consecutive to count 4, with credit for 0 DAYS time served, the term of INITIAL CONFINEMENT is 1 YEAR, the term of EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS. Court STAYED sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 3 YEARS.

AS TO COUNT 4: The court sentenced the defendant to serve 68 DAYS in the House of Correction, consecutive to count 2, with credit for 68 DAYS time served. A TIME SERVED DISPOSITION.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION/EXTENDED SUPERVISION
- Serve 180 DAYS in HOC as Condition Time, STAYED pending review, as to count 2.
- Batterers Intervention program.
- Mental health evaluation, take all prescribed medications.
- AODA assessment, comply with recommended treatment.
- Absolute sobriety with random UA's and SCRAM.
- No contact with victim S.A.C. unless approved by the court.
- Obtain/maintain employment.
- Write a letter of apology to S.A.C. after programming is completed.
- No contact with firearms.
- DV assessments imposed.
- Pay all MANDATORY court costs, fees, and surcharges including: DNA & DV surcharges to be paid during period of probation, if revoked to be paid by defendant's prison funds at a percentage to be determined by the DOC, remainder to be paid during the period of extended supervision; failure to pay will result in a civil judgment subject to any applicable collection procedures. 
- Court WAIVES all non-mandatory court costs, fees, and surcharges due to inability to pay.
- Provide DNA Sample.

*Court finds defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program OR the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.
*Court advised defendant of right to seek post conviction relief.
*Court advised due to felony conviction the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession, and defendant's voting rights are suspended and may not vote until civil rights are restored.
